  "chunk_index": 32,
  "summary": "Dr. Campbell questions Lucy about the dinner she prepared, which consisted of cream of mushroom soup, curry chicken rice, a cream wine dessert, and bacon chicken liver. Lucy specifies that the soup contained mushrooms, chicken broth, milk, cheese flour, and lemon juice. Campbell, noting that his investigation into Lucy's background shows she has no improper connections to the family members Cedric, Harold, or Alfred, collects leftovers of the curry, mushroom soup, and a spicy sauce from a clay jar for testing. Campbell expresses concern for Emma and Mr. Corin Soop, desiring to protect them from the potential harm sought by Corin's sons regarding the inheritance.\n\nCampbell informs Bacon that his preliminary tests confirm the presence of arsenic in the curry, suggesting the poisoner used arsenic to mimic the appearance of mushroom poisoning to mislead investigators. He notes that Miss Esperanza was the only person not poisoned, though he considers the possibility she ingested a smaller dose to avoid suspicion. He advises Bacon to inform the victims they have been poisoned to disrupt the murderer's plan.\n\nA phone call from a nurse reveals that the situation has worsened: Alfred has died. Bacon explains to Claddock that the nurse was overwhelmed while caring for Corin Soop, Emma, Alfred, Harold, and Cedric. While the nurse was attending to a noisy Corin Soop, she provided Alfred with tea containing glucose, after which he died. While Johnstone suggests the death might be a relapse, Campbell suspects continued arsenic poisoning. Claddock observes that Alfred's death provides no benefit to the heirs, whereas the death of the old man would.",
